// EXPECT_RUNTIME_PANIC requires failed: x % 2 == 0
//
// Plan 140 Ф.4 (D24 amend), acceptance F5: SAFE DEGRADE without Z3. When the
// compiler is built WITHOUT `--features z3-backend` (or run with the Trivial
// backend, `NOVA_SMT_BACKEND` unset / =trivial), the `proven_contracts` set is
// empty/smaller → essentially every contract is treated as unproven and is
// therefore runtime-checked in release. A violation still aborts fail-fast
// (safe, just no elision speedup) rather than being silently erased.
//
// `requires_even` has `requires x % 2 == 0`. A non-linear/modular predicate
// like this is NOT discharged by the linear-arithmetic TrivialBackend, so it
// stays runtime-checked under the no-Z3 degrade path. `main` calls it with `7`
// (odd), violating the precondition → `nova_contract_violation(
// NOVA_CONTRACT_PRE, ...)` → stderr + abort() → nonzero exit, in RELEASE.
//
// This fixture is run in two configurations to prove the degrade is safe:
//   * default Trivial backend (NOVA_SMT_BACKEND unset) — simulates no-Z3;
//   * a compiler binary built WITHOUT `--features z3-backend`.
// Both must abort identically. (Under a full Z3 build the predicate is still
// unproven for arbitrary x, so it also aborts — degrade only changes WHICH
// contracts get elided, never whether a real violation aborts.)
//
// Should-abort test: sole assertion is EXPECT_RUNTIME_PANIC (nonzero exit +
// structured stderr message). No stdout assert (`abort()` skips stdout flush).
// `UNREACHABLE` after the call never prints.

module plan140.t6_no_z3_degrade

fn requires_even(x int) -> int
    requires x % 2 == 0
=> x / 2

fn main() Io -> () {
    ro _ = requires_even(7)
    println("UNREACHABLE")
}
